body:
>Under the terms of the agreement, Xilinx stockholders will receive >a fixed exchange ratio of 1.7234 shares of AMD common stock for >each share of Xilinx common stock they hold at the closing of the transaction.

AMD is currently $91.47 & XLNX is currently $141.43. If you are getting 1.7234 shares of AMD per XLNX share...by that calculation, aren't you better off buying XLNX? Obviously, everything is influx and you don't know what the final prices would be. With that being said, would it be  a good idea to long XLNX?

author: SmallParade
body: Probably a combination of things. The usual post-earnings profit taking. Improved outlook for Intel after the CEO change. Retail investors who typically pour money into AMD getting distracted by GME. And big money investors getting wary due to the upcoming merger with XLNX. Many stocks will trade flat for months going into a big merger. We’re seeing that with CRM and NVDA too.

author: someonesaymoney
body:
No... just no.

It is a completely shit company in terms of innovation and has been milking it's Client and Server divisions to get those record revenues.  They've milked and underdelivered to customers so much that everyone is turning against them (Apple and Microsoft).  

They've lied for years on 10nm progress and now 7nm keeps pushing out.

They will make money for sure, but don't think any of their buy ins as moonshots will pay off.  They've fucked up acquisitions like Habana, Nervana.  McAfee was laughable.  Altera semi made sense, but they fucked them up enough to where Xilinx has surpassed them.  IoT, Memory, Drones, Autonomous Driving, 5G, Graphics, are all bets that will fail because of lack of execution and innovation.

It's not the previous CEOs fault.  He was just coasting and everyone knew.  You can't expect a CFO to have grand technical vision.  More like BK who completely fucked up the company.  Incoming CEO Pat will take at least 2-3 years to shake things up, if at all.  The cultural and managerial issues of the company at the lower levels, coupled with incompetence at the Board level doesn't bode well.

author: CowboyDodge
body: Bought following the post-earnings dip and added today. It's damn near impossible to get their chips and everybody wants them - there's still a huge shortage. Should ease if they can increase production, and the acquisition of Xilinx (solid, solid company) should help as well. Chips aren't going anywhere - they're going to end up in just about everything going forward, and AMD makes some of the best. I think it's a good time to get in.

author: ec429_
body:
Oh man I hope so, I work for XLNX and have hundreds of RSUs... 300 buck AMD would buy me a house all by itself.

But I think you're being over-optimistic.  Ignoring inflation I'd say $150 is a more likely AMD price target.

author: Goddess_Peorth
body:
I do some firmware engineering for my day job, here is my take: (disclosure: I own shares of AMD)

1) Intel got a new CEO. A lot of smart market people don't understand tech well enough to understand that Intel's problem wasn't business leadership, it was technical leadership and risky engineering choices that bit them in the ass. These are long engineering cycles, and a CEO can't fix it, nor can he fix the loss of trust from technical customers (who don't even like CEO-types, generally)

2) Same people don't understand the way the embedded market is going to more mixed chips, with different types of cores that can be programmed in different ways, and how the Xilinx purchase sets AMD up for success in the next round of engineering. Eventually this will clarify for them.

3) Related to 2, it isn't obvious to all outside observers yet that the embedded market and the server market are converging because of cloud computing. Horizontal scaling replaced vertical scaling in the datacenter, and now it is going back the other way with vertical scaling of the formerly-horizontal architectures; in other words, you used to buy big iron servers with fast CPUs, they switched to large clusters of small servers, now that is maturing into large clustered servers with super-fast IO that you can't get from a traditional cluster. This will likely destroy Intel's datacenter dominance.

4) AMD didn't have the ability to scale up production to maximize their revenue during the pandemic sales surge, and they're competing for the same fab time as the "chip shortage" in the news. That will continue to temper their stock volatility.

None of this is likely to change in the short term. If you still like the stock, grow your position, but it won't move until it does. If they're successful at integrating the Xilinx technology into competitive datacenter products, they could pull ahead for decades. They've always had the best engineering, but a lack of funding. They used to have weak business leadership, but it has improved a lot over the past decade.

Oops, didn't mean to type that many words! lol

body: The restricted access is a result of liquidity issues by the app brokers, not pressure from the hedge funds. I mean, sure there's no real way to disprove the latter isn't at play too. author: bored2death2
body: Completely agree with your point.  I \*was\* emotional about the trade, mostly pissed off at myself for not following my rules. I generally don't do covered calls AND when I do I get out of them well before loosing 10x the original sell price.  But I got over it quickly and soon found another thing to get frustrated with myself over.  Sure $ZBRA is a great stock and selling PUTs is a great way to make some scratch...but I didn't avoid their options who has a pretty large gap in the BID/ASK coupled with a low volume? Hard to buy back at times.  And while I didn't loose money - it took me three days to get rid of vertical PUT spread.  Only after I broke up the legs was I able to manage it.
